@node OpenStreetMap Tile Server,  , Running the Application with docker-compose, Running the Application with docker-compose
@subsubsection OpenStreetMap Tile Server
@cindex OpenStreetMap Tile Server
@cindex Map tile server
@cindex Tile Server, maps

Two other @code{docker-compose} files can be used to create a map tile server
using the @url{https://github.com/Overv/openstreetmap-tile-server,Docker
container for OpenStreetMap tile server}

One imports the @url{@value{osmurl},OpenStreetMap} data.  The other runs the
tile server after the data has been imported.

Elevation data can be made available to the container as follows:

@enumerate
@item
Create an external volume for the elevation data.  (It is necessary to
create the volume, even if no elevation data is available.):

@example
$ docker volume create elevation-data
@end example

@item
To copy elevation data files to the volume, stream the data from a tar
file via a helper container to the volume as follows:

@example
$ tar -zcf elevation-data.tar.gz *.tif
$ CID=$(docker run -d -v elevation-data:/elevation-data busybox true)
$ cat elevation-data.tar.gz | docker cp - $CID:/elevation-data/
$ docker container stop $CID
$ docker container rm $CID
@end example

It is necessary to use the tar file method as that seems the only way to
copy the data to the root of the volume.
@end enumerate

Import map tile data as follows:

@enumerate
@item
The import process temporarily requires a lot of memory.  You may need to
create and mount a swap file:

@example
$ sudo dd if=/dev/zero of=/swap bs=1G count=2
$ sudo chmod 0600 /swap
$ sudo mkswap /swap
$ sudo swapon /swap
@end example

@item
Create Docker volumes for storing any elevation data, the database and
caching of map tiles:

@example
$ docker volume create osm-data
$ docker volume create osm-tiles
@end example

@item
It is recommended to use a small region to minimise resource usage.

The default set in @code{./.env} imports OSM data for Monaco.  To import
another region,
e.g. @url{https://download.geofabrik.de/europe/isle-of-man.html, the
Isle of Man}, override the environment variables in @code{./.env}, e.g.:

@example
$ export DOWNLOAD_PBF=https://download.geofabrik.de/europe/isle-of-man-latest.osm.pbf
$ export DOWNLOAD_POLY=https://download.geofabrik.de/europe/isle-of-man.poly
@end example

The run the import with:

@example
$ docker compose -f docker-compose-map-import.yml up
@end example

The process must complete without error.  Check the final output carefully.
If it fails, it is necessary to delete and re-create the Docker
@code{osm-data} volume.

@example
$ docker volume rm osm-data
$ docker volume create osm-data
@end example

@item
Once the import completes successfully, run the map tile server:

@example
$ docker compose -f docker-compose-map-server.yml up -d
@end example

To stop the tile server:

@example
$ docker compose -f docker-compose-map-server.yml down
@end example

@end enumerate

