@section Using QEMU for Development and Testing
@cindex Using QEMU for Development and Testing
@cindex QEMU

@url{https://www.qemu.org,QEMU} can be used directly instead of using
Vagrant for creating development and test environments, by setting up
the QEMU image similarly to how the Vagrant setup scripts expect the
environment to be configured.

@enumerate

@item
Download and startup the QEMU @code{qcow2} image.  Ideally download a
version that corresponds with the Vagrant box version referenced within
the @code{Vagrantfile} in the Trip Server source distribution tarball
being used.

Example command to create and start a
@url{https://fedoraproject.org/server/download/,Fedora server QEMU
instance} on macOS:

@enumerate a

@item
Create the @code{qcow2} image.  This example creates the image based on
the downloaded @code{qcow2} image as a backing file. (Note that
specifying a size is optional.  The Fedora base was 6G and the system
install completed with 1.5G to spare):

@example
$ qemu-img create -b Fedora-Server-KVM-38-1.6.x86_64.qcow2 \
-F qcow2 -f qcow2 fedora-38.qcow2 6G
@end example

@item
Start the image...

Fedora example on a Linux host:

@example
$ sudo qemu-system-x86_64 -name Fedora_38 -M accel=kvm \
-cpu host -m 2G \
-drive file=fedora-38.qcow2,if=none,id=hd -device \
virtio-blk-pci,drive=hd \
-nic user,hostfwd=tcp::2222-:22,hostfwd=tcp::8080-8080 \
-nographic
@end example

The above example uses the @code{-nographic} option which runs the
server headless.  It also forwards port 2222 on the host to port 22 on
the guest, allowing you to SSH into the guest, e.g.:

@example
$ ssh -p 2222 vagrant@@localhost
@end example

Fedora example on a macOS host:

@example
$ sudo qemu-system-x86_64 \
-name Fedora_38 -M accel=hvf -cpu host -smp cpus=2 -m 2G \
-drive file=fedora-38.qcow2,if=none,id=hd \
-vga virtio \
-device virtio-blk-pci,drive=hd \
-usb -device usb-tablet -device usb-audio \
-display cocoa,show-cursor=on \
-nic vmnet-bridged,ifname=en1
@end example

The last line creates a bridged network for the Wi-Fi device named
@code{en1}.  This setting requires the command to be run as root to
create the network bridge on the host.

@item
The version of Fedora in the above example uses
@url{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_Volume_Manager_(Linux),LVM}
to manage logical partitions.  If you created the image with a larger
size than the original backing file, we now need to resize the LVM
partition in the container, then resize the file system on the
@code{/dev/mapper/sysvg-root} partition.  Resizing is only required if
you specified a size when creating the image and need the additional
space.

If you want to increase the image size subsequently, shutdown the
instance and resize it with e.g. @code{qemu-img resize fedora-38.qcow2
+5G} to increase the image size by 5G.  Then follow these instructions
to resize the underlying file system.

Run @code{sudo parted /dev/vda} interactively.  The interactive command
@code{help} provides help on the available commands.  Use @code{print
free} to see the available space.  Resize the @code{lvm} partition,
e.g. @code{resizepart 3 10GB} with the third @code{END} parameter being
whatever then @code{End} column shows for the end of the free space.
Exit @code{parted} with @code{quit}.  Alternatively, use @code{sudo
cfdisk /dev/sda} for another interactive command line tool to resize the
partition.

Resize the LVM physical volume with @code{sudo pvresize /dev/vda3}.
Then resize the volume with @code{sudo lvresize -l100%VG sysvg
/dev/vda3}.  Finally, resize the root file system with @code{sudo
xfs_growfs /}.

@end enumerate

@item
Create a @code{vagrant} user in the QEMU instance.  On most systems,
this will be by using the @code{adduser} command.

On Debian:

@example
$ sudo adduser vagrant
@end example

On FreeBSD, install the @code{bash} package with @code{pkg install bash} then
run @code{adduser} interactively with.

@item
Create the @code{vagrant} folder that would normally be mapped to the
Trip Server source folder.

@example
# mkdir /vagrant
# chown vagrant:vagrant /vagrant
@end example

@item
Upload the @code{trip-server} source distribution tarball to the QEMU
instance.

@item
Extract the source to the @code{/vagrant} folder, e.g.:

@example
# cd /vagrant
# su - vagrant -c 'tar -C /vagrant --strip-components=1 \
  -xf /home/vagrant/trip-2.2.2.tar.gz'
@end example

@item
Execute the Vagrant scripts:

@example
# bash -x /vagrant/provisioning/bootstrap.sh
# bash -x /vagrant/provisioning/bootconfig.sh
@end example

If all has gone well, @code{trip-server} will have been built in the
@code{/home/vagrant/build} folder and installed at
@code{/usr/local/bin/trip-server}.

@item
To test the server, open the firewall in the Fedora guest with:

@example
$ sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp
$ sudo firewall-cmd --list-ports
@end example

You can make the firewall change survive reboots with @code{sudo
firewall-cmd --runtime-to-permanent}.

Run @code{trip-server} and navigate to the host's IP address and port
8080 using a browser and the login page should be shown.

@end enumerate

